{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:59:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:59:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16778"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.77,0,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67275"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52727"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5175"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22384"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67275"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcetylcholine is a neurotransmitter that has several key functions throughout the body. Pathways involving acetylcholine are a common target for medications - for example neostigmine, rivastigmine and donepezil. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the common primary mechanism of action of the drugs neostigmine, rivastigmine and donepezil?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Block acetylcholine release from nerve terminals","Prevent enzymatic breakdown of acetylcholine","Increase acetylcholine synthesis","Stimulate acetylcholine receptor expression","Directly stimulate muscarinic receptors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeostigmine, rivastigmine and donepezil are examples of acetylcholinesterase inhibitors - ie they \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent enzymatic breakdown of acetylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E at cholinergic synapses by the enzyme acetylcholinesterase. This results in accumulation of acetylcholine and enhanced cholinergic transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking acetylcholine release from nerve terminals\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease rather than increase cholinergic transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases acetylcholine synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as these drugs do not affect the production of acetylcholine, only its breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of acetylcholine receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E would be too slow to account for the rapid effects of these medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese drugs work indirectly by increasing endogenous acetylcholine levels; they do not \u003Cstrong\u003Edirectly stimulate muscarinic receptors.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcetylcholinesterase inhibitors are used therapeutically in conditions like myasthenia gravis and glaucoma. They can also cause toxicity, as seen in organophosphate poisoning, due to excessive cholinergic stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors prevent the breakdown of acetylcholine in synapses, leading to increased cholinergic transmission.","Anticholinesterases have both therapeutic uses (myasthenia gravis, glaucoma) and toxic effects (organophosphate poisoning).","The effects of acetylcholinesterase inhibition include increased muscarinic and nicotinic receptor stimulation throughout the body."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16778"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T12:46:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T12:46:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9469"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67275"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":